# The ALTER TABLE statement in Structured Query Language allows you to add, modify, and delete columns of an existing table.  
This statement also allows database users to add and remove various SQL constraints on the existing tables.
Any user can also change the name of the table using this statement.

  1) ALTER TABLE ADD Column statement in SQL
  
  Syntax*
  ALTER TABLE table_name 
  ADD column_name datatype;

  e.g.
  ALTER TABLE mahe_sql.empdata
  ADD EMail_id varchar(50);

  2) ALTER TABLE MODIFY Column statement in SQL
  Syntax*

  ALTER TABLE table_name
  modify column_name data_type;  -- Earlier column EMail_id data type was varcharm now its Int.

  e.g.
  ALTER TABLE mahe_sql.empdata
  modify EMail_id int;


  3) ALTER TABLE RENAME Column statement in SQL
  Syntax*
  ALTER TABLE table_name
  RENAME COLUMN old_column_name to new_column_name;

  e.g.
  ALTER TABLE mahe_sql.empdata
  RENAME COLUMN EMail_id to E_Mail;

  4) ALTER TABLE RENAME Table_Name statement in SQL
    Syntax*
     ALTER TABLE old_Table_name
    RENAME TO new_table_name;

    e.g.
    ALTER TABLE empdt	
    RENAME TO EMPDATA;
  


  

  
